      "content": "<div class="single-post-content">
            <p>I grew up thinking coffee was the forbidden fruit.</p>
<p>After nearly two decades of believing coffee could stunt my growth, science has shown that my mom was wrong all along. “What I tell patients is, if you like coffee,” Dr. Peter Martin, the director of the Institute for Coffee Studies at Vanderbilt University, says, “go ahead and drink as much as you want and can.”</p>
<p>Research has consistently proven the health benefits of coffee — its caffeine content improves focus, increases metabolism and has powerful antioxidant effects on drinkers. As an avid coffee drinker myself, I am at times baffled by those who refuse to drink it. My roommate, for one, often can’t stand the taste and complains of stomach upset. Another friend of mine says she wishes she could drink coffee but finds the beverage anxiety-inducing.</p><!--Ad Injection:random--><script type="text/javascript"> 

