" data-medium-file="https://i1.wp.com/dailynexus.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/4-9-14-caffeine-e1400646130687.jpg?fit=188%2C250&amp;ssl=1" data-large-file="https://i1.wp.com/dailynexus.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/4-9-14-caffeine-e1400646130687.jpg?fit=300%2C400&amp;ssl=1" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-55419" src="https://i1.wp.com/dailynexus.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/4-9-14-caffeine-e1400646130687.jpg?resize=300%2C400" alt="4-9-14 caffeine" width="300" height="400" srcset="https://i1.wp.com/dailynexus.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/4-9-14-caffeine-e1400646130687.jpg?w=300&amp;ssl=1 300w, https://i1.wp.com/dailynexus.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/4-9-14-caffeine-e1400646130687.jpg?resize=188%2C250&amp;ssl=1 188w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" data-recalc-dims="1"></a>One-third of the world’s population consumes coffee on a regular basis. The average American drinks three cups of coffee a day. Many people — especially college students — indulge in the revitalizing magic of coffee. So, what effects does this favorite drug of choice have on the body?</p>
<p>Coffee contains caffeine, which has a nearly immediate effect on the body; it takes about 15-45 minutes for coffee to take its full effect, and it stays in the body for about two to seven hours. Shortly after you take that first sip, the heart starts to beat faster, body temperature rises and, most importantly, you feel more awake. This is due to how coffee affects the nervous system.</p>
<p>University of California, Santa Barbara professor of Psychological &amp; Brain Sciences, Karen Szumlinski, said that caffeine inhibits a particular receptor in the nervous system.</p><!--Ad Injection:random--><script type="text/javascript"> 

